    <exercises xml:id="practice-rings-intro" permid="Pav">
      <title>Practice Problems</title>
      <exercise permid="zRx">
        <statement>
          <p permid="vaA">
            Consider <m>\Z_8</m> as a ring.  
            <ol permid="Flk">
              <li permid="OEW">
                <p permid="bDi">
                  What are the <em>units</em> in this ring?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="uMf">
                <p permid="HKr">
                  Is <m>\Z_8</m> a commutative ring?  A division ring?  An integral domain?  A field?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="aTo">
                <p permid="nRA">
                  What if we look at <m>U(8) = \{1, 3, 5, 7\}</m>.  These all have multiplicative inverses mod 8.  Is <m>U(8)</m> a field?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="mxM">
          <p permid="UID">
            <ol permid="gIA">
              <li permid="Hax">
                <p permid="TYJ">
                  The units are the elements of the ring that have multiplicative inverses.  So here, <m>1, 3, 5, 7</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="nhG">
                <p permid="AfS">
                  <m>\Z_8</m> is a commutative ring (with unity) but is not a division ring, and thus not a field.  It is also not an integral domain because it contains zero divisors, such as <m>2</m> and <m>4</m> (since <m>2\cdot 4 = 0</m>).
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="ToP">
                <p permid="gnb">
                  <m>U(8)</m> is a group under multiplication, but is not a field.  We would still need addition to work, and this subset is not a subring, since <m>U(8)</m> is not closed under addition.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="fYG">
        <statement>
          <p permid="bhJ">
            Define <m>\Z_3[i] = \{a+bi \st a, b \in \Z_3;~ i^2 = -1\}</m>.
            <ol permid="lst">
              <li permid="zvY">
                <p permid="Muk">
                  How many elements are there in <m>\Z_3[i]</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="fDh">
                <p permid="sBt">
                  Construct addition and multiplication tables for <m>\Z_3[i]</m>.  
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="LKq">
                <p permid="YIC">
                  Is <m>\Z_3[i]</m> a ring?  A commutative ring?  A commutative ring with unity?  A division ring?  An integral domain?  A field?  Use your tables to justify your answers.  
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint permid="SEV">
          <p permid="Kjy">
            There will be 9 elements.  When doing the tables, reduce mod 3 after each calculation.  For example, <m>2i\cdot 2i = -4 = 2</m>.
          </p>
          <p permid="qqH">
            <m>\Z_3[i]</m> will be a field, so a commutative division ring with unity and an integral domain.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="MfP">
        <statement>
          <p permid="HoS">
            How can you tell from the addition or multiplication tables whether a ring <m>R</m> is an integral domain?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="yMe">
          <p permid="APM">
            We only need to look at the multiplication table.  Unless we include rows and columns for 0 (which is unnecessary, since <m>0 \cdot x = 0</m>), an integral domain will have no zeros at all in the multiplication table.  Any zero in a row and column that are not zero would say that that row and column are zero divisors.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="smY">
        <statement>
          <p permid="nwb">
            We let <m>\Z[x]</m> be the ring of polynomials in the variable <m>x</m> with integer coefficients.  So <m>x^2 + 5x + 7 \in \Z[x]</m>, for example.
            <ol permid="RzC">
              <li permid="rRz">
                <p permid="EPL">
                  Is <m>\Z[x]</m> a commutative ring?  With unity?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="XYI">
                <p permid="kWU">
                  Explain how you know that <m>\Z[x]</m> is not a field.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="EfR">
                <p permid="Red">
                  What if we considered <m>\R[x]</m>, allowing real coefficients instead of just integer coefficients.  Is <em>this</em> a field?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="eTn">
          <p permid="gWV">
            <ol permid="MPJ">
              <li permid="kna">
                <p permid="xlm">
                  Yes, <m>\Z[x]</m> is a commutative ring with unity.  <m>1</m> is a polynomial.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="Quj">
                <p permid="dsv">
                  Look at the elements <m>x \in \Z[x]</m>.  There is no polynomial we can multiply by <m>x</m> to give us 1.  It's not just that <m>1/x</m> is not a polynomial, it is that any polynomial times <m>x</m> will result in a polynomial of degree at least 1.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="wBs">
                <p permid="JzE">
                  As we have above, it is not the coefficients that are the problem (although if <m>\R[x]</m> we do have more units, since now <m>5</m> has an inverse).
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
