      <exercise permid="QPI">
        <statement>
          <p permid="sfU">
            Let <m>R</m> be a ring.  For <m>x \in R</m>, we write <m>nx</m> to mean <m>x + x + \cdots + x</m> (            <m>n</m> times).  What is <m>(nx)^2</m>?  What about <m>(nx)^3</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="XoO">
          <p permid="Zsw">
            Let's try <m>(2x)^2</m>.  This is really <m>(x+x)(x+x)</m>, which we can apply the distributive property to.  We get <m>x(x+x) + x(x+x) = x^2 + x^2 + x^2 + x^2 = 4x^2</m>.  It should be clear this generalizes (although a careful proof would use induction).  So <m>(nx)^2 = n^2x^2</m>.  In fact, <m>(nx)^p = n^px^p</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="wWR">
        <statement>
          <p permid="Ynd">
            Suppose that <m>R</m> is a ring such that <m>x^3 = x</m> for all <m>x \in R</m>.  Prove that <m>6x = 0</m> for all <m>x \in R</m>.
