    <exercises xml:id="practice-rings-ideals" permid="nDf">
      <title>Practice Problems</title>

      <exercise permid="pss">
        <statement>
          <p permid="QIE">
          Let <m>\phi:R \to S</m> be a surjective (onto) ring homomorphism.  Prove that if <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> both have unities <m>1_R</m> and <m>1_S</m> then <m>\phi(1_R) = 1_S</m>.  
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="PKp">
          <p permid="lGO">
          We have <m>\phi(1_R) = \phi(1_R1_R) = \phi(1_R)\phi(1_R)</m>.  But the unique element <m>x \in S</m> such that <m>ax = a</m> and <m>xa = a</m> for <m>a \in S</m> is <m>x = 1_S</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="VzB">
        <statement>
          <p permid="wPN">
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring with unity and <m>\phi:R \to S</m> a (not necessarily surjective) homomorphism.  Could <m>1</m> be in the kernel?  Show that if it is, that <m>\phi</m> is the trivial homomorphism <m>\phi(x) = 0</m> for all <m>x \in R</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="vRy">
          <p permid="RNX">
          We know that the kernel <m>K</m> of <m>\phi</m> is an ideal.  If <m>1 \in K</m>, then <m>a\cdot 1 = a \in K</m>, since <m>K</m> absorbs products.  This means that every element of <m>R</m> is in the kernel, so the homomorphism is trivial.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="BGK">
        <statement>
          <p permid="cWW">
          Consider the ring <m>R = \Z_3 \times \Z_3</m>.  This contains 9 elements, each of the form <m>(a,b)</m> where <m>a, b \in \Z_3</m>.  
            <ol permid="JVd">
              <li permid="NzD">
                <p permid="axP">
                Find the two non-trivial ideas of <m>R</m> and the subring of <m>R</m> that is not an ideal.  Call this non-ideal subring <m>B</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
            <ol permid="qcm">
              <li permid="tGM">
                <p permid="GEY">
                Give an example of what goes wrong if you try to form the quotient ring <m>R/B</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="bYH">
          <p permid="xVg">
            <ol permid="sWS">
              <li permid="ZNV">
                <p permid="mMh">
              The ideals are <m>\{(0,0), (1,0), (2,0)\}</m> and <m>\{(0,0), (0,1), (0,2)\}</m>. 
              The subring that is not an ideal is <m>B = \{(0,0), (1,1), (2,2)\}</m>.  To see this is not an ideal, note that <m>(0,1)\cdot (1,1) = (0,1) \notin B</m>, so <m>B</m> does not absorb products.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="FVe">
                <p permid="STq">
              Consider two cosets <m>(0,0) + B = B</m> and <m>(1,0) + B</m> (the other coset would be <m>(0,1) + B</m>).  There is no problem with defining these cosets, and in fact <m>R/B</m> will be a quotient group (since <m>B</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>\Z_3\times \Z_3</m>).  
                </p>

                <p permid="zaz">
              Thus the problem must be with multiplication.  We would have <m>((0,0)+B)((1,0)+B) = (0,0)+B</m>.  But another name for <m>(0,0) + B</m> is <m>(1,1)+B</m>, and <m>((1,1)+B)((1,0)+B) = (1,0)+B \ne B</m>.  So coset multiplication is not well defined.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="hNT">
        <statement>
          <p permid="Jef">
           Give an example of rings <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> and a function <m>\phi:R \to S</m> which is a group homomorphism but not a ring homomorphism.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint permid="IfQ">
          <p permid="CEZ">
           You know that if the kernel of <m>\phi</m> happens to be an ideal, then <m>\phi</m> will automatically be a ring homomorphism, by the Fundamental Homomorphism Theorem.  So we must find a ring <m>R</m> that has a subgroup (which would automatically be a normal subgroup) which is not an ideal.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="NVc">
        <statement>
          <p permid="plo">
           Here is a nice application of homomorphisms.  For each <m>n</m>, we  consider the canonical homomorphism from <m>\Z</m> to <m>\Z/n\Z</m>.  It is easier to think of this as the homomorphism that sends <m>\Z</m> to <m>\Z_n</m>, which maps <m>a \in \Z</m> to <m>a \pmod{n}</m>.
            <ol permid="Wjv">
              <li permid="mcn">
                <p permid="fhI">
                 Consider the equation <m>11x^2 - 8y^2 +  109 = 0</m>.  Note that <m>(7,9)</m> is a solution to this equation.  Explain how we can use this fact and a homomorphism to be sure that there is a solution in <m>\Z_5</m> to the equation <m>x^2 + 2y^2 + 4 = 0</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="Sjw">
                <p permid="LoR">
                 Prove that the equation <m>x^2 - 7y^2 - 24 = 0</m> has no integer solutions.  You might want to use a homomorphism from <m>\Z</m> to <m>\Z_7</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="yqF">
                <p permid="rwa">
                 Prove that <m>x^2 + (x+1)^2 + (x+2)^2 = y^2</m> has no integer solutions.  Hint: <m>\Z_3</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint permid="Uui">
          <p permid="iMi">
           The point of all this is that if there is no solution to the corresponding equation in <m>\Z_n</m>, then there is no solution in <m>\Z</m>.  When you apply the homomorphism to both sides of the equation, you use the homomorphism property to reduce every coefficient mod <m>n</m>.  And then you only have <m>n</m> possible values for each variable.  Better yet, if you pick <m>n</m> that makes one of the coefficients 0, you only have to check the other one.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <solution permid="omZ">
          <p permid="ecp">
           (b) Suppose there was some pair <m>(a,b) \in \Z^2</m> that was a solution to the equation.  Apply the natural <m>\phi:\Z \to \Z_7</m>: 
            <me permid="NNY">
             \phi(a^2 - 7b^2 - 24) = \phi(0)
            </me>
            <me permid="tVh">
             \phi(a)^2 - 0 \phi(b) - 3 = 0
            </me>
           But this says that <m>3</m> is a square in <m>\Z_7</m>.  Checking each element in <m>\Z_7</m>, we find this is not the case, so no such <m>(a,b)</m> can exist.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
    </exercises>


