      </exercise>

      <exercise number="C2" permid="GqD">
        <statement>
          <p permid="hGP">
      Consider the ring <m>\R[x]</m> of polynomials in the variable <m>x</m> with real coefficients.  We can divide polynomials using long division, which results in some remainder.
            <ol permid="ixN">
              <li permid="Day">
                <p permid="wfT">
            What is the remainder when you divide <m>3x^4 - 7x^3 + x^2 - 3x + 7</m> by <m>x^2 + 1</m>?  (Perform the long division, but you only need to submit the results: quotient and remainder.)
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="jhH">
                <p permid="cnc">
            What do you get when you substitute <m>x^2 = -1</m> into <m>3x^4 - 7x^3 + x^2 - 3x + 7</m>? 
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="PoQ">
                <p permid="Iul">
            Coincidence?  What sort of polynomial will you always get as a remainder when dividing a polynomial by<m>x^2 + 1</m>?  What sort of polynomial will you always get when substituting <m>x^2 = -1</m> into a polynomial?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="vvZ">
                <p permid="oBu">
            Consider the quotient ring <m>\R[x]/\langle x^2 + 1\rangle</m>.  Use an evaluation homomorphism (with <m>a = \sqrt{-1}</m>) to prove that this quotient ring is isomorphic to <m>\bC</m> (the complex numbers, <m>\bC = \{a+bi \st a,b \in \R; i^2 = -1\}</m>).
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>


          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

