      <title>The Chinese Remainder Theorem for Rings</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="rDu">
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring and <m>I</m> and <m>J</m> be ideals in <m>R</m> such that <m>I+J = R</m>.

          <ol permid="ijv">
            <li permid="uMi">
              <p permid="tVk">
                Show that for any <m>r</m> and <m>s</m> in <m>R</m>, the system of equations
                <md permid="IuB">
                  <mrow>x &amp; \equiv r \pmod{I}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x &amp; \equiv s \pmod{J}</mrow>
                </md>
                has a solution.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="aTr">
              <p permid="act">
                In addition,
                prove that any two solutions of the system are congruent modulo <m>I \cap J</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="HaA">
              <p permid="GjC">
                Let <m>I</m> and <m>J</m> be ideals in a ring <m>R</m> such that <m>I + J = R</m>.
                Show that there exists a ring isomorphism
                <me permid="oBK">
                  R/(I \cap J) \cong R/I \times R/J
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

